      {
        "id": 2219581,
        "name": "Subu Ramachandran",
        "username": "Subu_Ramachandran",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/8797f3/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2017-07-14T20:18:00.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"GregT\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/gregt/48/625_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> GregT:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In case you don\u2019t want to read an entire Asimov article, they\u2019re usually some version of the same thing, so here\u2019s a handy summary.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Hey! Try wine from this grape or region!</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Unfortunately, some producers used new oak! They\u2019re ruining everything!</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Thank god some producers do things the traditional way, whatever that was.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Those last producers are the best. They make food-friendly wines.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>The pendulum is swinging back to the traditional producers.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>The end.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Haha, so true, especially of late\u2026</p>\n<p>But its good that Eric dwells into off-beat regions/ grapes. There\u2019s enough drum roll for mass-planted, mass-marketed, fanboy wines that are increasingly homogeneous.</p>\n<p>I hope he mixes the content up to avoid becoming monotonous!</p>",
