      {
        "id": 2219707,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2017-07-14T22:45:05.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Subu Ramachandran\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Subu Ramachandran:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But its good that Eric dwells into off-beat regions/ grapes. There\u2019s enough drum roll for mass-planted, mass-marketed, fanboy wines that are increasingly homogeneous.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>While I agree with the sentiment, I felt that the piece did not seem to be grounded in the depth of research that he brings to his best pieces.</p>\n<p>Of tangential relevance, but folks looking to know more about Pepe might be interested to read an article I wrote about him in Noble Rot a while back: <a href=\"https://wfkelley.com/2016/11/22/emidio-pepe-and-the-road-less-travelled/\" class=\"inline-onebox\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">Emidio Pepe and the road less travelled \u2013 William Kelley</a></p>",
